questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following statements is/are correct regarding image formation in the plane mirror?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A. Image is erect.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;B. Image is real.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;C. Image is laterally inverted.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;D. The image size is the same as that of the object.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Plane mirrors&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;are simply flat mirrors without curves. These&amp;nbsp;are polished surfaces coated with mercury such that they reflect most of the light falling on them.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/06/F1_J.K_2.6.20_Pallavi_D8.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 450px; height: 275px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;image&amp;nbsp;formed by a&amp;nbsp;plane mirror&amp;nbsp;is always&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;virtual and erect.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The image formed is &amp;lsquo;virtual&amp;rsquo; because it is a copy of an object formed at the location from which the light rays appear to come.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The distance of the image &amp;lsquo;behind&amp;rsquo; the mirror is the same as the distance of the object in front of the mirror.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The image and object are the equal distance from a plane&amp;nbsp;mirror&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Image is&amp;nbsp;laterally Inverted&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;means&amp;nbsp;is inverted from left to right, like an image seen in a mirror. The right side of the object appears as its left side, and vice versa.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/06/F1_J.K_2.6.20_Pallavi_D9.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 153px; height: 139px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The image size&lt;/strong&gt; formed by the plane&amp;nbsp;mirror&amp;nbsp;is the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;same as the object size.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The distance of the image &amp;lsquo;behind&amp;rsquo; the mirror is the same as the distance of the object in front of the mirror.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, from the above-mentioned points, it becomes clear that the image formation in the plane mirror is not real.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Shadow Formation&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A shadow is a&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;black spot&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;that is formed when an&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;opaque object comes into the path of light.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This happens because&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;light travels in a straight line&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and if there is any&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;obstacle in between the light&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;could not pass through&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;it.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;formed on the screen&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;which could be a wall or anything like that.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The size of the shadow depends upon the distance between opaque objects and sources of light.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/02/F1_Prakash_Anil_15.02.21_D2.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Shadow is basically blocking the path of the light.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A shadow formation requires a&lt;strong&gt; light source, a screen, and an opaque object.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Shadow&amp;#39;s shape depends upon the shape of the object but the exact shape cannot be decided by the shadow.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This can be demonstrated by making different shapes using our hands.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We can see the difference in the shape of the object and the shape of the shadow.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Colour has no role to play in shadow formation as objects&amp;nbsp;of different colours and the same size will have the same size of shadow in the same situation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Also, the shadow is a dark patch, so no effect of colour can be seen on it.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/22/03/60dd8352e36d90c2e7063671_16469762045421.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Shadow can predict the exact shape of the object. is the only incorrect statement.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Violet, Indigo, Blue, Green, Yellow, Orange, Red&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The order of colours of the rainbow is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Violet, Indigo, Blue, Green, Yellow, Orange, Red&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We can remember it as &lt;strong&gt;VIBGYOR&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;VIBGYOR &lt;/strong&gt;stands for Violet, Indigo, Blue, Green, Yellow, Orange, and Red.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;VIBGYOR&lt;/strong&gt; is the representation of colours after the&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;splitting of white light&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;Trick to remember colours of the Spectrum of White Light - VIBGYOR |  GK-Tricks.com&quot; src=&quot;https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-Wlbtijugu00/VWFkU9e-BQI/AAAAAAAAAO8/ngQLIymFB3s/s1600/Trick%2Bto%2Bremember%2Bcolours%2Bof%2Bthe%2BSpectrum%2Bof%2BWhite%2BLight%2B-%2BVIBGYOR.gif&quot; style=&quot;height: 147px; width: 300px; border-width: 1px; border-style: solid;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formation of Rainbow:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&lt;span&gt;In&amp;nbsp;rainbow&amp;nbsp;formation both refraction and internal reflection takes place.&lt;/strong&lt;span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is caused by the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;dispersion of sunlight by tiny water droplets&lt;/span&gt;, present in the atmosphere.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;droplets&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;act like a small&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;prism&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;refract and disperse&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;the incident sunlight, then&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;reflect it internally&lt;/span&gt;, and&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;finally refract it again&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;when it comes out of the water droplet.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A&amp;nbsp;rainbow&amp;nbsp;is always formed in the&amp;nbsp;direction&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;opposite&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to that of the Sun.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The formation of a&amp;nbsp;rainbow&amp;nbsp;is shown below:&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/07/2020-07-11_2043.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 300px; height: 231px; border-width: 1px; border-style: solid;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Tyndal Effect is caused&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;by the scattering of light.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The light is scattered when it is passed through a colloid which is a term given to a mixture that contains particles (in the range 1-1000 nanometer) of an insoluble substance suspended in a solvent.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Tyndal Effect makes the beam of light passing through the mixture to be highly visible.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The effect can be easily observed when passing a torchlight through a mixture of milk and water.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Refraction.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Concept&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Refraction of Light:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;bending of the ray of light passing from one medium to the other medium&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is called&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;refraction&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F1_J.K_8.5.20_Pallavi_D3.png&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/05/F1_J.K_8.5.20_Pallavi_D3.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 280px; height: 178px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;refraction of light&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;takes place going from one medium to another because the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;speed of light is different in the two media&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;greater the difference&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;in the speeds of light&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in the two media, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;greater will be the amount of refraction&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;medium&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in which the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;speed of light is more&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is known as an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;optically rarer medium&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;medium&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in which the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;speed of light is less&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is known as an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;optically denser medium&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Explanation&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The swimming pool depth is more than what it appears.&amp;nbsp;This happens due to the refraction of light.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When light travels from one medium to another it bends, and the light rays from the bottom of the pool get bent when they exit the water&amp;#39;s surface.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Our eyes don&amp;#39;t take refraction into the account so the swimming pool appears less deep than it actually is.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;So,&amp;nbsp;the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;phenomenon of refraction&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;causes&amp;nbsp;swimming pool depth to be more than what it appears.​&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

